            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text after Rizzone 2009, checked against photograph</note></app>
                    <app loc="1"><note>Manganaro restores a christogram at the start of the line, which can only be hypothetical</note></app>
                    <app loc="3"><note>Rizzone: Πο-|[θή]του; Manganaro πρ(εσ)β(ύτερος) </note></app>
                    <app loc="4"><note>Manganaro: ἐν κώ(μη)ͅ Μηνηνίου; ἰου(λίου) or ἰου(νίου) is possible.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p><!--translation(s) - add @xml:lang for 'en' or 'it' to div--></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>There seems no clear basis on which to decide whether Gregorios or his father was the presbuteros, since the ending is lost in the abbreviation, but it clearly affects the debate regarding celibacy of priests. Manganaro assumed the word referred to Gregorios; Rizzone to his father Po[--]tos.<!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--Enthade kete w en makaria  mnemei Gregorios uios Pothetou presbuterou zesas ete kb teleuta de en Kuriwi mene iouniou/iouliou indiktiwnos h. So it's for Gregorios, son of a priest. Note that Manganaro originally read this as recording the kwme of Meneion, i.e. Menae / Mineo, but this reading is rejected and replaced with a date by month by Feissel in BE, by Rizzone, and by Felle per litteras to Manganaro. The inscription is known by a photograph given to Manganaro by a pupil, provenance unknown and current location unknown. Rizzone speculates that the formula is similar to another from Mineo and so perhaps from this region.--></p>
            </div>
